text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Linguistic Discrimination Against Spanish Accents%0a:Author: ayush_d%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 15:58%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210504-192252-755860#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 12:22-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210504-192252-755860#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aExample of accentism with Spanish accents%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aLink: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fQim2iZdBUg%0a%0aIn the link above, comedian Erik Rivera demonstrates examples of various types of Spanish accents and stereotypes. Although his intention is not racist in nature, as it is specifically for comedic purposes, certain linguistic and grammatical cues stand out when identifying language discrimination in this example. %0a%0aFor example, when pronouncing the sentence “How are you?”, Rivera stretches out every vowel sound pronounced to provide emphasis on the “twang” that underlies the Spanish accent. He also replaces vowel sounds like [t] in touch with [θ] and [i] in “peepee” with [ɪ]. These cues simply allow the listener to understand that Rivera is employing a Spanish accent in particular, as he never outright states it.%0a%0aExpanding on the latter example, he forgoes using the proper word (derogatory language warning) “penis” and instead replaces it with “peepee”. Not only does this imply a limited vocabulary of the average native Spanish speaker when speaking English, but it also implies that the manners of Spanish men are improper when speaking to women since they see them as sexual objects. Rivera jokes in the next sentence that the accent grants “no credibility”, which further reinforces the notion.%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
